**Abstract**  
This essay examines “Improvising While Black” from Mayfeild Brooks. Mayfeild Brooks is a dancer, choreographer, activist, artist, and cultural worker. “Improvising While Black” serves as a form of oral history, revealing the functions of improvisation in Black culture. Examples of improvisation functions are the ability to act as a practice of survival and memory, bringing the trauma of the past or of the group's ancestors. Within this essay, it will be revealed how improvisation can bring out the practices of survival, memory, and resistance within Black culture and the diaspora. In addition, by drawing from Mayfeild Brooks and Karen Nelson’s conversation and analyzing the themes that were discussed within their conversation, and treating them as various types of motifs. The digital visualizations figures shown were created with Voyant Tools, which highlight the patterns in the transcript and will be compared with real-world evidence of Brooks' dances. While viewing Brooks’ work, I observed that she uses her body, an extension of black bodies, to speak memory through improvisation.

**Oral History Analysis**  
The spreading of oral history is the backbone of the survival of diaspora and cultural memories, one of the main themes in Mayfeild Brooks’ storytelling within her pieces. Diaspora, memory, embodiment, improvisation, and survival are key themes within oral history in dance. Each of these key themes reflects recurring motifs in Brooks' work and the transcript.   
In the conversation “Improvising While Black”, Brooks explores themes of diaspora and how they can intersect with improvisation among Black people. An example of this is when Brooks stated early in the conversation, “I think of myself as a descendant of the Middle Passage, and that ocean is always in my body when I move” (Brooks, 2016). This quote discusses the pillar of survival, and that quote from Brooks shows her comparison of improvisation to the afterlife of slavery. This articulation of diaspora allows improvisation to be a practice that carries and remembers the migration and displacement of people.  
For Brooks, their body is a carrier of ancestral memory. They state, “the body remembers even when you don’t want it to–trauma, refusal, laughter, all of it comes back when I improvise” (Brooks, 2016). Brooks’ gestures become a form of memory for themselves; dance allows for memory or past events to be reactivated and stored within their own body. This interpretation aligns with the idea that improvisation is not performed, but rather emerges from layers of lived experiences.  
	The act of improvising is embodied knowledge for Brooks. Brooks describes feeling disoriented and untrustworthy within predominantly white spaces of improvisation and dance. “In white dance spaces, I often feel ungrounded, like I can’t trust the floor or the touch offered to me” (Brooks, 2016). In this quote, one can understand and feel from Brooks that embodiment is not about stability, but rather about someone carrying knowledge of mistrust and the body’s rejection of the norms of neutrality. The mistrust and ungroundedness come from the racial imbalance. Coming together with black people in any space brings comfort to other black individuals because they feel accepted.   
	The concept of survival becomes a central motif within this transcript and Brooks' work. Brooks emphasizes that “I improvise because it’s the only way I know to keep living–it’s not decoration, it’s survival” (Brooks, 2016). This quote shows Brooks' trauma connected to their persistence. Improvisation then becomes a method by which Brooks, and could extend to other black dancers, create a place for themselves and use their bodies to cope with their trauma. Dance allows them to keep moving and survive.  
	Overall, these five themes showcase how oral history functions as both a testimony and a theory. This allows improv to be a space for diasporic survival, enabling others to learn movements and teach them about their cultural or ancestral traumas, allowing others to perform and use their bodies to carry the message.

The size of the words shows how frequent specific words were used within the transcript. The word clusters such as “body”, “trust”, and “dancing” highlights the reflections Brooks had on the functions of improv. Which can translate to improvisation functions not only as a form of technique but as a form of survival.

**Embodied Insights**  
The videos of Mayfield Brooks make the motifs from Brooks’ oral history transcription recirculate. In each dance, it showcases motifs that resonate with Brooks' statements, showing how oral history is not only carried through speech, but it can also be embodied through practice. In video 1, the motifs I tracked were Brooks going on her tippy toes, extending her arms, and having intense head shakes. These gestures can go with Brooks’ reflection on instability and disorientation. Brooks states, “Falling is the only way I can practice trust, but it always carries risk” (Brooks, 2016). These motifs can show people that Brooks may be trying to communicate a sense of searching, instability, or disorientation. However, in video 2, the performance starts with a black screen, which could relate to a veiling of information. This moment can align with Brooks’ state, “sometimes the only thing I can do is hide, disappear, or refuse to be seen, and that too is a survival practice (Brooks, 2016). By having the screen black for a moment during the performance, it allows the viewers and audience not to expect what they usually do from dance performances. Having the black screen acts as a tool of refusal. By refusing to give the people what they want but still performing it, Brooks can feel invisible, which is a tool of survival. Lastly in video 4, I recorded the motifs: clacking rocks together, swaying arms, shushing, and exhaling loudly. Throughout this video, I felt like the performance was a remembrance of our ancestors. In my observation, the clacking of rocks created a rhythm. Striking the rocks together can bring memories of ancient history. Brooks could have done this to activate memory to act as an active archive. In conclusion, these embodied motifs showcase Brooks bringing oral history through speech and performance.   
**Theoretical Connections**  
	Brooks’ oral history, as presented in the transcript and her performances, alongside diasporic framers and embodied works, for survival. Ananya Chatterjea and Nadine Georgeg-Graves are two people who can future prompt Brooks’ improvisation within diaspora, memory, and survival. Furthermore, Chatterjea observed that “history stands in the way of memory’, and it plays with different dimensions of time \- history, memory, futurity” (Cristi, 2022).  This quote highlights how histories can complicate the body’s attempt to heal and remember. This idea aligns with Brooks’ use of improvisation as a form of embodied memory. Additionally, in the same way Brooks sees movement as a way to refuse, shapeshift, or survive, George-Graves gives us something to look at from a different lens. Georg-Graves has a concept of “diasporic spidering” which weaves the identity through “webs of memory, connection, becoming” (McDermott, 2024). This concept can align with Brooks’ unique beliefs within improv, such as performing cultural memories, like clacking rocks together.   
**Conclusion**  
In conclusion, pairing Brooks’ transcript with the digital visualization I created and the performance motifs I tracked reveals how Brooks’ improv can bring survival as an embodied memory and ancestral/cultural refusal. Using Voyant allowed for recurring motifs to be highlighted and personify key themes within the transcript. Joining oral history, digital analysis, and embodied memory shows the importance of how vital the survival of diaspora can be to the performer and the viewer. Overall, Brooks’ conversation backs up that improvising while black allows for their body to not only be a tool of movement, but it can also be a tool to showcase their living archive.
